text:
sexual assault is common among female students of all ages, races, and ethnicities. one in five women in college experiences sexual assault. studies show that students are at the highest risk of sexual assault in the first few months of their first and second semesters in college. in addition, women who identify as lesbian, bisexual, or gay are more likely to experience sexual assault on college campuses than heterosexual women. (https://www.womenshealth.gov/relationships-and-safety/sexual-assault-and-rape/college-sexual-assault) 
from a survivor of sexual assault in college: ‚Äúdefinitely using alcohol and drugs can contribute to sexual assault on campus. but it is also men‚Äôs attitudes towards women, race, and identity that play a major role that explains why rape and assault are so common.‚Äù #ngocswny #16daysofactivism #hearmetoo #orangetheworld #endvaw #metoo #believesurvivors #wewillnotbesilenced #timesup #standup #consentissexy #consentculture #sexworkiswork #notaskingforit

text:
today's #rapemyth is one of the longest standing and most deeply engrained in society. it shows in how rape cases are tried in court (recent #clothingisnotconsent uproar is a case in point), reported in the press, and how victims and survivors are treated. 
on day 2 of #16daysofactivism, let's make this perfectly clear: no woman ever asks to be raped. ever. it's time to stop victim blaming. 
#orangetheworld #hearmetoo #metoo

text:
self-esteem is the belief in your own worth, which is a basic human need. being understood, respected, and taken seriously is basic to the development of self-esteem.

traumatic experiences have a direct effect on our self-esteem and self-worth. either we learn to survive it or we will continue to hold ourselves back. it‚Äôs very easy to develop the victim mentality and believe that we cannot persevere. it doesn‚Äôt have to be that way, we can choose to change how we allow the traumatic experience to affect us. through rewiring our thoughts and beliefs, turning the negative into positive, we can transform the way we view ourselves. 
as a survivor of sexual assault, i had to learn how to love and forgive myself. for years i felt less than and unworthy. i constantly allowed people to mistreat me. i felt a lot of anger towards others but i was most angry that i never protected myself. 
it wasn‚Äôt until i ended up in cognitive processing therapy and sought treatment for ptsd that i was able to learn the skills to develop my sense of self-worth. ¬†as with any change, consistency and lots of effort are required but if you are willing to put the work in, you will see results. 
it‚Äôs much like a tangled ball of yarn, if you are diligent and enduring it will eventually unravel.

1% better every day. 
the world is a better place with you in it üåéüíñ

opening pameran seni instalasi ‚Äúsaat itu aku‚Ä¶‚Äù
dalam rangka turut meramaikan kampanye 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan, jaringan kitasama yang diwakili oleh pamflet generasi, pusat kajian gender dan seksualitas, dan aliansi satu visi bekerja sama dengan enambelas film festival, hollaback, dan never okay project membuat seni instalasi pakaian penyintas kekerasan seksual "saat itu aku‚Ä¶". seni instalasi ini mengangkat 8 kasus kekerasan seksual yang dikisahkan melalui replika pakaian yang dikenakan korban ketika kekerasan seksual terjadi.
.
kami mengundang rekan-rekan penggiat isu perempuan, anak, dan ham untuk turut hadir pada opening pameran seni instalasi "saat itu aku‚Ä¶" yang dilaksanakan pada:
hari/tanggal	: selasa, 27  november 2018
waktu : 18.30-20.00
tempat	: paviliun 28, jl petogogan 1 no. 25, kby. baru, jakarta selatan.
.
informasi lebih lanjut dapat menghubungi 081347700988. terima kasih atas kerja sama yang baik, sampai jumpa! :)

text_retweet:
#repost @officialmuterkelly (@get_repost)
„Éª„Éª„Éª
"those who have never been in an #abusiverelationship struggle to understand how people remain in one for so long. if somebody was mistreating you, "why did you stick around?" they ask.
.
this is because we are conditioned to believe #abuse is always physical. on tv and in films, we see characters who are obviously evil. they are violent to their partners, shout at them aggressively, or even murder them in a fit of rage. while this does happen, it's not a true representation of the abuse many others experience.
.
unfortunately, for many people, when they try to leave these relationships they are so bonded to their abuser that they return. others don't try to leave at all, and are only freed from the clutches of the abuse when they are discarded.
.
an abusive relationship with a #narcissist or #psychopath tends to follow the same pattern: idealisation, devaluation, and discarding. at some point, the victim will be so broken, the abuser will no longer get any benefit from using them. they may have totally bankrupted them, or destroyed their confidence, or worse, and they move on to their next target.
.
however, once they are gone, the victim - or survivor as thomas calls them at this point - can finally start coming round to the idea they were abused. they can grieve, and finally see the damage that was being done, and realise it wasn't their fault.
.
that's when the healing can really begin, thomas says, and the survivor can realise that they were targeted not because they were weak, but because they had so much to give."
.
full article at: https://uk.businessinsider.com/trauma-bonding-explains-why-people-often-stay-in-abusive-relationships-2017-8
.

text:
important ‚Ä¢

stop associating depression with the religion!!! i'm writing this because i'm very angry and upset on the mentality of some people who just can't accept the fact that depression is real! thank god that you haven't experienced anything like depression or anxiety but please stop telling the victims "it's all in your head". -

you're not depressed, you're just not close to allah", "you don't recite quran, that's why you're feeling like this", "you don't need a doctor, you need to offer namaz". staaaahhhp!!!!! -

offering namaz and reciting quran, is undoubtedly the most peaceful thing in this world. and it most definitely helps in curing the depression. but please please please understand that depression needs more than just a peace of mind to cure. brain is an organ, just like any other organ. 
and still if you do not understand, kindly stop insulting those who are suffering. kindly stop suggesting that they don't need a doctor. stop!!!
.

because she knew beauty 
could never be taken away..

text:
setiap 1 dari 3 wanita indonesia pernah mengalami kekerasan setidaknya sekali dalam seumur hidupnya, tanpa memandang tingkat pendidikan, status sosial atau usia mereka. korban sering terdiam karena mereka disalahkan dan kesaksian mereka diragukan.

untuk memperingati 16 hari aktivisme tahun ini melawan kekerasan berbasis gender, para influencer indonesia menyampaikan pesan yang kuat untuk mengakhiri kekerasan terhadap perempuan dan anak perempuan. dalam video tersebut, para influencer menekankan pentingnya bagi setiap orang untuk berbicara, berdiri dalam solidaritas dengan para penyintas dan pendukung dan bertindak untuk menghentikan normalisasi kekerasan terhadap perempuan dan anak perempuan.

kekerasan terhadap perempuan bukan hanya masalah perempuan, tetapi juga masalah setiap orang. sekarang saatnya untuk berbicara agar suara kita didengar. ‚óè‚óè‚óè every 1 out of 3 indonesian women has experienced violence at least once in her lifetime, regardless of their level of education, social status or age. victims are often driven into silence because they are blamed and their testimonies are put in doubt.

to commemorate this year's 16 days of activism against gender based violence, indonesian influencers delivering a strong message to end violence against women and girls. in the video, the influencers emphasize the importance for everyone to speak out, stand in solidarity with survivors and advocates and act in order to stop normalizing violence against women and girls.

violence against women is not just a women‚Äôs issue, but also everyone‚Äôs issue. it is now time to speak up and for our voice to be heard.

#hearmetoo #16days #orangetheworld  #metoo #unwomen #genderequality

come molti di voi sanno, ieri √® stata la giornata mondiale contro la violenza sulle donne, ma la nostra lotta continua e per questo scriviamo oggi. 
negli ultimi giorni era impossibile non imbattersi in rivendicazioni di ogni tipo. ma le nostre battaglie non si possono ridurre a un brand social, a un rossetto sulla guancia, a un post su facebook, a un #metoo di un giorno.

combattiamo insieme questa cultura per combattere la violenza.

text: how do you surf big waves when you are very new to surfing?! ride the whitewaters!!! here coach @jon_paul_phillips guides @nattorres__ @bridgetdear and @jmebbink on some high rotation whitewater boot camp drills. we think these women got more waves in 90 minutes than the dudes out the back got all day! they got to practice turning, weight distribution, and timing. this time next year they will be making drops out the back like csc alums @__.minia.__ @cnizar @bdhussain and @cclalonde. and here is also a psa for male surfers who think they are being ‚Äúkind‚Äù by telling women surfers what they ought and ought not do: why don‚Äôt you ask whether they need your help first? this works for any beginner of any gender. unsolicited advice is never welcome ‚Äî nor is a lack of faith in the human potential to overcome large obstacles and hairy situations. don‚Äôt believe us? then we suggest tuning into the @wsl jaws and honolua bay events today!!! some serious activation of human potential will be on display! and just to be clear we only advise those that seek our advice ‚Äî it is a mutually consensual situation. in the era of #metoo a lot of the discourse around consent has been about the violation of bodies, but consent should also apply to #mansplaining and other micro aggressions. thanks to @cclalonde for pushing us to put these thoughts out there. you rule catee!!!

text:
nominated for the 2018 financial times and mckinsey business book of the year‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
'a vital book. new power can light a flame bright enough to outshine the glinting fangs and tiki torches' - russell brand‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
for most of human history the rules of power were clear: power was something to be seized, and then jealously guarded. under this 'old power' we lived in a world of rulers and subjects.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
now, we all sense that something has changed. from #metoo to harvey weinstein; corbyn to trump; from youtube sensations to darker phenomena such as the emergence of isis ‚Äì in our new hyper-connected world, ideas and movements can spread and flourish with astonishing force and speed.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
in new power, jeremy heimans and henry timms confront the biggest story of our age and trace how new power is the key to understanding where we are and will prosper in the 21st century.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
drawing on examples from business, politics, popular culture and social justice, as well as case studies of organisations like lego and ted, they explain the forces that are changing the course of our age.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
in a world increasingly shaped by new power, this book will show you how to shape your future.‚†Ä

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
will you think about me?
again, 
every morning when
you dress up;
wearing my favourite colour,
reminiscing my picture in your eyes
and wishing that if our destiny was
not as dark as your kohl.

will you think about me?
again,
when your hair strands
would kiss your cheek;
making your face an art to adore
and when your skins longs for my touch
which you had left behind your ears.

will you think about me?
again,
when you cross the road of doubts
need a hand to hold,
fingers to caress,
and when your eyes would 
search a name in the lines over your palm.

will you think about me?
again,
when your love would leak
from the promise which was broken
and need someone to mend;
your drenched trust,
and show a path to your hope 
which etches for home.

but, you know my questions hits me hard.
for, i know
by now you have already thought about me.

darshan sanghvi.
(@darshansanghvi28)
.
.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
do you have thoughts and feelings about the recent reports of sexual harassment on campus?

we do, and we invite you to join us  in the prevention of future agressions.

plucked is an artistic project by and for uoe students to empower each other in defending and advocating for ourselves and others in the face of sexual harassment.

we'll be staging a play on the subject next year, but before that we are creating a series of open workshops and activities so all students's voices can be heard in any way they want, by sharing their stories and their art, wich will be featured (if you want to) in our theatre play.

for more information on how to get involved, connect with our social media accounts:
- instagram @plucked.essex
- facebook: plucked project university of essex

image by @danieladeveikyte

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
hey yoga teachers: if you teach vinyasa, or lead teacher trainings, or ever ever ever teach the history of yoga, then you need to go listen to @jbrownyoga‚Äôs new interview with karen rain, who was an early devotee of pattabhi jois, and whose refusal to be silent about the sexual assault she suffered under his tutelage is changing the face of ashtanga. that‚Äôs her there in the headstand at left, in this 1993 @yogaworks primary series video. next to her are richard freeman and tim miller, who went on to become ashtanga icons. why didn‚Äôt she? because she was so traumatized by sexual assault at the hands of her ‚Äúguru‚Äù that she left her beloved practice completely, a troubling abusive pattern many fellow mysore practitioners witnessed and never called out.
.
the bottom line is that the vinyasa practice we know and love is largely a product of a serial sexual predator. gah. seriously. ü§¶üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è so if you teach yoga history (especially to starry-eyed newbie teachers!) and leave this shit out, you are lying to your students. and doing a disservice to everyone who will ever study with them.
.
the shadow side of yoga is real. it‚Äôs not pretty and it‚Äôs not fun to talk about. but karen does a powerful job here of sharing her story, calling out privilege, and saying it like it is, even when it‚Äôs uncomfortable. her voice shakes. listening, i feel her vulnerability and her bravery. and i recommit to telling the truth about the often-misogynistic history of yoga, even when it feels icky and uncomfortable.
.
we owe it to our students. be brave. do the hard work. they deserve the truth. it‚Äôs more than just rainbows and unicorns. ü¶Ñüåà
.

text:
#didyouknow | norma jeane baker was born june 1st, 1926 to gladys pearl mortensen and an unknown father. she lived with her mother until the age of 8. back in 1934, gladys had prepared a hot bath for baby norma to drive the bad spirits of the world away, but the water was so hot it almost burnt baby norma to death. that‚Äôs when gladys was hospitalized in a mental health institution: she was schizophrenic, and could not look after her child. she lived at the institution until her death at the age of 86. 
gladys worked as a technician assistant for the studios, and tried to compensante for her failure at becoming an actress with delusional (and often psychologically abusive) behaviors towards norma. she claimed her baby‚Äôs father was a famous actor (clark gable) who left the pair because he didn‚Äôt want norma, and every sunday she‚Äôd drive her through the hollywood hills pointing at every star‚Äôs mansion. this is how baby norma started developing her dream of becoming a hollywood actress.

________________________________

gladys, from the script of love is blonde:
norma jeane, i swear you're half blind sometimes as well as half dumb. can't you see? open your eyes
and see? (passes her a photograph of clarke gable). that man is your father.
_________________________________

throughout jennifer's presentation you will be asked to think about the question, "where do you want to go?" she will explain what your true north is and how you can become aligned with your true north in everything you do.

text:
re: my recent post about my assault & arrest, i am absolutely overwhelmed by the positive support i have received in response üò≠üòç. idk what i did to deserve it but i am completely taken by surprise and deeply grateful. thank you so much from the bottom of my heart.
.
trauma like this is incredibly hard to navigate and painfully isolating, especially given the repeated re-traumatizing by individuals in power whose jobs are to protect.
.
.
to everyone who made me feel heard by way of acknowledgement (simply liking/reacting to post, dming, commenting, etc), know that your actions meant the world to me. to those who reached out and acknowledged despite us not being very close or having talked in years, know that i see/feel you and your support holds as much weight as anyone else‚Äôs. i love you all!
.
.
the criminal case against my abuser closed ~1 month ago, and i have so much more i want to say and share. yes, i have learned and been through so much‚Äîfrom being tailed by a private investigator hired by my abuser to being asked to testify in trial and practicing multiple times with the da. no, i do not feel that, all things considered, the proper amount of justice was served to fit the crime‚Äîthe da let him plead out last minute, 2 days before the trial, with no criminal record, after verbally promising me so much more after my arrest.
.
.
these past 8+ months have been a clusterfuck of mismanaged expectations, lots of overpromising, and plenty of underdelivering. i am still trying to find my peace: some days i do, and some days i don‚Äôt.
.
. 
i try to embrace and trust the process. i find that writing helps, as does putting myself out there sometimes. if my story can positively impact just one person out there, i‚Äôll be happy.
.
.
nobody warned me of the potential repercussions of ‚Äúdoing the right thing,‚Äù and i wish someone had. i wish i had had access to someone else‚Äôs similar experience, from which i could draw learnings and advice from. hindsight is 20/20 of course, but i would‚Äôve done many things differently. i hope i can help fill that void for someone out there by leaving written breadcrumbs of my experience behind.
.
.
#metoo #believesurvivors #fuckthepolice

text:
girls, we have come a long way! üëè
.
feeling inspired today to share the excitement for the times! evolution is inevitable, not only physically üåèbut mentally and emotionally too. when i was in college a mere decade ago, i was surprised to learn that "feminist" was a pretty dirty word (i even wrote a column on women's rights called "the f word"... and the name was well-received) üì∞
.
stating out loud i was a feminist was almost like admitting something shameful. it was rarely a word i saw in media - not on tv, not online, not in magazinesüòê now and then an advancement for women would pop up in pop culture, but the f word was seriously never used.
.
maybe not coincidentally, the word seemed to blow up with the expansion of smart phones and social "connectivity." instagram became a thing. hashtags became a thing. #metoo became a thing. and suddenly feminists everywhere no longer had to hide üôå and women who weren't sure what the word meant began getting an education just by turning on the news!
.
although the circumstances (lots of sexual abuse coming to light) that has banded women together is unfortunate to say the least, the power that's coming from us admitting what we've gone through and fighting back is a truly beautiful thing üåø
.
for this, i'm not sure all credit can go to technology, but it's definitely helped üì≤and in the mean time, we're using it to make the world a better place.
.
watch out! women at worküíóüíó
.

thanks for abusing me and showing me just how much i‚Äôm worth.

text:
‚ùå‚ùå i‚Äôve never shared this story publicly ‚ùå‚ùå
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i sat there, tears streaming down my face. i couldn‚Äôt believe this was happening. it was so surreal.
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i had never felt this extent of pain before. everything i wanted, no longer wanted me.
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i sat there in the court room as we awaited our number to be called so we could stand in front of the judge and dissolve our marriage.
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
in between fits of uncontrolled sobbing, i noticed something strange that day. ‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
there were roughly 40 of us in that court room and yet, the judge and i were the only men. could this actually be? where were all the men?
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i knew that my presence that day was voluntary however, i felt responsible that even if it meant to stare down the barrel of the gun, i was taking responsibility for being equal parts to where we currently found our relationship.
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
were there no other men present because men don‚Äôt care? of course we do however, there‚Äôs something going on deeper below the surface.
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
we‚Äôre hard wired to give our gift of a solution, we like to fix things, to provide. ‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
the challenge for me was that i didn‚Äôt say i wanted a divorce, i just lowered my standards by accepting ‚Äúgood enough‚Äù.
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
at the time, i thought for me to be a good husband, i needed to provide money, a house, resources, etc.
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it was a lot simpler than that. what i truly needed to provide was emotional presence. for myself and my loved ones. ‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
if you‚Äôre a man reading this and you‚Äôre not exactly sure how to provide this, send me a dm and let‚Äôs continue this conversation ‚Äúoff line‚Äù.
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
if you‚Äôre a woman reading this and you agree or disagree, comment below or dm me.
‚Ä¢‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

text:
there is 1 thing every child has that most adults don't have.

something that we need to take time to rekindle and grow within ourselves... know what it is?

curiosity.

you know how parents go on and on about how annoying their kids are for asking so many questions?

well, that's the wonder and curiosity of a child.

that insatiable hunger for knowledge drives children to ask questions about everything... "why is the sky blue?" "why does that man have such a long beard?" why, why, why... now let me ask you this... why is this important?

and what does this have to do with ptsd?

well, let me tell you... we all lose that sense of wonder, that curiosity that drives us to search, and to learn, and to try new things!

we lose the curiosity that used to drive and excite us... as adults we're left lifeless and dull, living the same monotonous day over and over again.

we're too afraid to go against the grain... too afraid to try something new because we don't want to look stupid... too afraid to make a mistake or be wrong... this fear turns us into lifeless robots.

this fear prevents us from trying something new... and it all stems from us crushing that curious part of us... the part that we all have inside.

the part that you have inside, and the part you might have forgotten about.

in order to get a different result in life, we need to do something different.

we can't keep living the same robotic life we've been living.

we need to change, and we need to try new things.

if you don't change, and if everything stays the same, guess what you will get?! more of the same!

you need change.

you need a child's curiosity.

you need to feed that part of you because it's the part of you that feeds your soul.

when you learn something, experience something, or see something new it excites you!

when you feed that childlike curiosity inside of you, you start to learn and you start to live.

does this all make sense to you?

without curiosity we aren't going to change things... and without change we are just going to stagnate and decay... there's some food for thought for today!

is there anything new you should be trying?

„Éª„Éª„Éª
hey yoga teachers: if you teach vinyasa, or lead teacher trainings, or ever ever ever teach the history of yoga, then you need to go listen to @jbrownyoga‚Äôs new interview with karen rain, who was an early devotee of pattabhi jois, and whose refusal to be silent about the sexual assault she suffered under his tutelage is changing the face of ashtanga. that‚Äôs her there in the headstand at left, in this 1993 @yogaworks primary series video. next to her are richard freeman and tim miller, who went on to become ashtanga icons. why didn‚Äôt she? because she was so traumatized by sexual assault at the hands of her ‚Äúguru‚Äù that she left her beloved practice completely, a troubling abusive pattern many fellow mysore practitioners witnessed and never called out.
.
the bottom line is that the vinyasa practice we know and love is largely a product of a serial sexual predator. gah. seriously. ü§¶üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è so if you teach yoga history (especially to starry-eyed newbie teachers!) and leave this shit out, you are lying to your students. and doing a disservice to everyone who will ever study with them.
.
the shadow side of yoga is real. it‚Äôs not pretty and it‚Äôs not fun to talk about. but karen does a powerful job here of sharing her story, calling out privilege, and saying it like it is, even when it‚Äôs uncomfortable. her voice shakes. listening, i feel her vulnerability and her bravery. and i recommit to telling the truth about the often-misogynistic history of yoga, even when it feels icky and uncomfortable.
.
we owe it to our students. be brave. do the hard work. they deserve the truth. it‚Äôs more than just rainbows and unicorns. ü¶Ñüåà
.

text: as the film and art worlds mourn bernardo bertolucci, now is as good a time as any to bring up the crucial fact that he filmed and condoned rape/sexual assault. this is a picture of maria schneider, who starred in bertolucci's last tango in paris. she revealed many years later that a sex scene she filmed for the movie was changed by bertolucci and costar marlon brando without her knowledge and without her consent. she said she felt raped and was never consoled before or after the incident. she died with little fanfare and with little publicity while the violent men who violated her continued to have hugely successful careers and many tributes after their death. this is, for lack of a better term, bullshit. schneider was a young woman looking for a break in a hostile industry. instead, she was assaulted and traumatized for the rest of her life. i don't care that bertolucci just died or that brando was a "good" actor (and most likely a closet case as well.) we need to reckon with the fact that #metoo does not just pertain to this era or place in time. it has been rampant and pervasive in this industry since its inception. we still hold these abusive men up on pedestals while we belittle and ignore their victims. bertolucci is a monster for ever allowing this to happen. it was his job to create a safe work environment for art to flourish and he failed at that most basic thing. so before you praise his work or the man himself, remember maria schneider and the price she paid for his "art". #hertoo #film #movies #bernardobertolucci #marlonbrando

ep.162-here‚Äôs my #interview with one of the contributors in my #consent book, #theconsentguidebook (www.theconsentguidebook.com), sex-positive and consent-positive speaker jean franzblau. we chat about her role as a cuddle party professional and she and her colleagues teach consent at their events. we also discuss ways to express our #boundaries to others. 
about consent guidebook contributor jean: jean franzblau is a sex-positive and consent-positive speaker who walks her talk. when she discovered the importance of her own sexual empowerment, she wrote a play about it and performed it in ten cities. when she realized how important hugs and affection were to her emotional and physical health, she founded @cuddlesanctuary ‚Äì which has already offered 300 events and served over 500 clients in los angeles. jean has presented at sexuality conferences on both coasts and for audiences around the country and abroad. she created the presentation sex after #metoo to share the message of consent to college campuses. jean has been featured on buzzfeed, good mythical morning and rolling stone. visit jean at http://cuddlesanctuary.com

reposting from @gmsp_foundation - #violenceagainstwomen is a crime of near epidemic proportions. one in four women in the uk will experience domestic violence in the course of her lifetime. and while it is a crime that is blind to whose life it affects ‚Äì rich and poor, young and old ‚Äì we know that many black, asian and minority ethnic women (bme) across the uk face additional hurdles seeking help and protection. - 40% of #bmewomen live in poverty. - bme and #refugeewomen experience higher rates of domestic homicide - are 3 times more likely to commit suicide than other women in the uk. - 50% of bme women victims of violence experience abuse from multiple perpetrators.

text:
i was sexually, physically, mentally, emotionally and verbally abused by my father and other people as a child. whenever i post something on this page i‚Äôm not trying to imply that we cannot overcome the sexual abuse. we can overcome sexual abuse to a certain degree in our lives. i don‚Äôt remember many normal memories of my childhood because the memories were overshadowed by the sexual abuse. sexual abuse took over my life as a child and destroyed everything and the simplest memories of a happy childhood. the sexual abuse will never fade away no matter how much healing or therapy i have worked through in my life. in fact i can say that i‚Äôve never been happier in my life like i am now but the memories are still there and can ruin some of my days. ptsd or complex ptsd is not something that you just turn off and on like a light switch for survivors. our minds can unexpectedly relive our past even if we don‚Äôt want to remember what happened to us as children. healing is a lifelong process that requires a lot of determination, courage, self care and consistency. there‚Äôs no magical wand, pill or religion that can take away the memories. yes i have found ‚Äúhealing‚Äù from the trauma of incest, child sexual abuse and human trafficking but i still work every single day to move forward and beyond from my past to be more than a victim.

survivors still remember the sexual abuse but through the healing journey, what changes is the control the pain has over the survivor‚Äôs life

don‚Äôt let anyone compare your healing process to other survivors of childhood sexual abuse.

so you want to go to the gym because you want to lose weight. you buy new shoes, a new outfit, and there is still this block that says "nope! if we lose weight bad things can happen." üåø
research shows that there is a mind-body connection related to trauma and weight-loss. your body is smart! it will store away fat and calories to protect itself.
üåø
high ace (adverse childhood experiences study) scores from divorce, poverty, physical and sexual abuse increase the risk of many health conditions and can lead to obesity.
üåø
researchers found that any kind of trauma must be dealt with first before successful weight loss takes place.

some people can wear their passions. with a fashion account called @gillertsgarments, @lexgillert‚Äôs #passionpreview is about what to wear: ‚Äúmy passion is fashion! i have always loved art, drawing and creating things, but i was never a self-proclaimed ‚Äòfashionista.‚Äô i played sports my whole life which meant i was in a uniform more than i was in regular clothes. i've always loved watching award shows and watching the extravagant gowns float down the red carpet, it was always a magical feeling for me. whenever i watched the shows i always thought ‚Äòi want to create that one day.‚Äô‚Äù
-
why fashion? ‚Äúfashion, whether you believe it or not, is truly the best snapshot of what is going on in our society right now. fashion can have a simple meaning, but it can also have a very complex meaning. simple meaning a classic white t-shirt and jeans or more complex like the fashion statements surrounding the #metoo movement. fashion also makes life fun! clothes really allow us to express our personal feelings and identities in ways other material things can‚Äôt.‚Äù
-
to someone not interested in fashion: ‚Äúwhether don't you keep up with what's going on in the fashion industry or you think it's all too superficial, a great outfit can make anyone look and feel amazing!‚Äù
-
to someone interested in getting started in fashion: ‚Äújust dive right in! there is really no one way to start because everyone is so different. start with the aspect of the design process that resonates with you the most (sewing, illustrating, or textile creation) and get creative!‚Äù

text:
finding your passion isn't about careers and money. it's about finding your real self. the one you've buried under everyone else's needs.
.
there was a time in my life that i didn't know myself. i didn't make time to take care of the mind or body i have. i seemed happy on the outside, sure. but beneath the surface was a torrent of storms and tidal waves.
.
admitting you need more is not weakness. doesn't make you less.
.
admitting you need more gives you strength. giving yourself more, makes you more. .
just take a chance. make a choice. make a change. what have you got to lose?
.

text: at the british film institute attending film screenings, meetings and workshops with angelina jolie, nobel laureate dr denis mukwege and other invited guests at the psvi film festival - fighting stigma through film üá¨üáßüé¨ the preventing sexual violence initiative (psvi) was launched by the british government to prevent the horrific issue of sexual violence and the systemic use of genocidal rape as a 'weapon of war' in conflicts such as the 1971 bangladesh liberation war/indo-pak war where around 400,000 women were raped by the pakistani military and islamist militias. the international community, however, has failed to learn the lessons from history and have been very slow to intervene and prevent such horrific crimes in recent years as we have seen from islamic state/daesh in the middle east to boko haram in africa. it was great to hear from actress &  psvi co-founder + unhcr ambassdor angelina jolie and other activists regarding this urgent issue. thanks to the foreign and commonwealth office for the invitation and organising such an outstanding film festival (the film 'city of joy' in particular is highly recommended). the fco also launched the 'murad code' on sexual violence - & pledging ¬£500,000 for victims of sexual violence globally - named after the indefatigable & inspirational 2018 nobel peace prize laureate nadia murad, a yazidi survivor of sexual violence & genocide perpetrated by the islamic state, who is now a global activist & founder of nadia's initiative. ‚úä‚úä‚úä #timetoact

text:
there has been a rapid expansion in knowledge and interest in trauma and abuse survivors because of the ongoing #metoo movement. this was not planned, but this timely element in my book (as i had the courage to share my #metoo story) has contributed to my ongoing quest to share how i used yoga as a part of my healing. people who are hiding abuse (whatever kind it is) are hiding it for many reasons. my hope is that coming forward as a silence breaker i can empower other people to do the same. you may very well know of someone who is in trouble or hiding something and afraid to come forward. by sharing my book, you may help someone. i was hiding behind a mask that looked like i had it all together. i didn‚Äôt. i received help at a treatment facility where i was treated for ptsd and healed. i now share my truth knowing that i was that person hiding, but no longer. i now wear my scars with pride. i‚Äôve received letters from women saying they had a similar experience and it gives me hope that collectively we can help each other. i'll be at the barnes & noble is la mesa this saturday from 1:00-3:00 if you want an autographed copy of my book, come by. the address is grossmont center, 5500 grossmont center dr #331, la mesa, ca 91942. we are not alone in our suffering, we are just alone in our silence. #yogawisdom is a real and intimate look into using yoga to move through my challenge in life and emerge empowered to help others. the book is an inspiring gathering of over 100 yoga teachers who share how they, too, use yoga to live a life of unlimited potential. if you know of anyone who is looking for a great holiday gift for someone who is interested in yoga, their health or hoping to find a tool to move through their own challenges in life please tell them about my book. the initial response in the first month has been incredible. thanks for your help in sharing with others. they will love you for it. .
#ptsd #ptsdawareness #inspiration #yogainspiration #yogi #yogaeveryday #yogaeverywhere #yogagirl

the united nations defines violence against women as "any act of gender-based violence that results in, or is likely to result in, physical, sexual or mental harm or suffering to women, including threats of such acts, coercion or arbitrary deprivation of liberty, whether occurring in public or in private life. the estimate that 1 in 3 women around the world have experienced either physical and/or sexual violence, mostly by an intimate partner is one that is widely cited today. whilst this is a worldwide figure, there is variation in the prevalence of violence seen within and between communities, countries and regions. even though data are scarce, we know that in humanitarian and emergency settings, linked to an increase in armed actors and a decrease in security as a result of broken social and protective networks, the risk to women of different forms of violence are even greater.‚Äù via @sofatim

text:
some people survive and talk about it. some people survive and go silent. some people survive and create. everyone deals with unimaginable pain in their own way, and everyone is entitled to that, without judgement. so the next time you look at someone‚Äôs life covetously, remember‚Ä¶you may not want to endure what they are enduring right now, at this moment, whilst they sit so quietly before you, looking like a calm ocean on a sunny day. remember how vast the ocean‚Äôs boundaries¬†are. whilst somewhere the water is calm, in another place in the very same ocean, there is a¬†colossal¬†storm @nikita_gill

in this #metoo era there can be overwhelming pressure to share your narrative. just remember you have the power and control to decide what you wish to share and keep to yourself. raising awareness around gender based violence also looks like giving people the power to choose their own tools for healing and providing them with options. it is always about giving the survivor the power.

shot taken a bit ago at the #metoo panel, mosaic literary conference 2018. üì∏: @mgyoungphotography

i spend a lot of time reading and learning about queer people‚Äôs lives. most of the time i am listening, because i know i have very strong ideas and can be really stubborn. i never want to be the person that prioritizes their judgement of the world over open, honest perception and understanding. sometimes this means that i don‚Äôt talk enough because i get lost listening. thank you to the mentor @robleswrites for inviting me out to speak, for giving me the platform to uplift queer and trans lives in the context of sexual violence, healing, and liberation; a conversation we are so often excluded from. shout out to the other writers on the panel with me. an hour listening to ya‚Äôll speak made my world so much larger. this is a reminder to speak, more often.

text:
a preview (this is just a quick snapshot & not a final work) of a new series that i've been working on with the working titles "stolen flowers" & "flowers from homes". what is your preferred title for this series?

i started this series to help engage my mind and body in learning to walk again. first in a rehabilitation centre, and then back at home - starting with walking just past one house and back, and now up to 5km at a time. sometimes i can manage walking my wonder dog sebastian ‚ù§. thinking about why i started the series and why i titled it stolen flowers is related to the #metoo hashtag that went viral earlier in the year. my past has been littered with damaging, secretive and painful events starting at an innocent and sheltered version of me at 16yo. when i first tried to speak out about what had happened to me to a psychologist and psychiatrist, they interpreted my anger, pain and inability to process the events as being a drug user & at the time i felt a huge betrayal of privacy as they shared this with my then school and my parents. the experience further damaged my soul and belief in the medical system. it took a long time to trust a psychologist, men and those close to me, let alone share snippets of these painful events. 
flowers have long been metaphors for innocence, sexuality and loss of innocence. sometimes the act of ripping or cutting a flower from its plant is a deflowering, a destruction of innocence, a cause of its inability to play a part in the plants future reproduction - a crack in the lifecycle. 
however, while these deep, dark thoughts have surfaced, there is also a pure, unadulterated joy in photographing these small natural miracles, having their scent pervade a room, and carefully arranging them to be lifted up as life symbols. 
i hope you enjoy this series - i have a few working photos to share while i'm in post-production of this series.

text: now. i know i birch a lot, but ima be okay. you see, i‚Äôve realized something. when you have problems with your pipes, well your water pipes, you call a plumber. when you have a problem with your other pipes you call a doctor. and when you have a huge problem like being human sex trafficked, you call experts in that field. they get me. they understand me. recently someone who i allege is involved asked me what my goal was with all of this. was it for revenge? i thought for a moment and answered that my goal was for a nationwide campaign against the type of porn i was in, drugged, unaware, and unresponsive. i see the other nameless faces in this type of porn and i must help them. #lifegoals

text:
for the first time in my life, i shared details about an event that happened 10 years ago and parts of it that i have never told a soul until this interview because i had a lot of shame around them.

also in this interview, kara the host of @madeforthat felt called to do the same.

listening back to this episode, i cringed, i had goosebumps, teared up a little, and wanted to throw up.

why?

because some of this is disturbing and may upset you.

it may also inspire you.

it may change your perspective.

it may challenge you.

it may piss you off.

it may trigger you.

in the end, this conversation needed to be had, and when we were recording i had no idea this would come up, but it did and i'm grateful it did.

join the conversation now.

text:
üëèüëèüëèüëè@regran_ed from @mercyiaspire -  the picture on the left is me 12 years ago! then a victim now a victor! .
.
i am one of the few fortunate to be alive. some  left in a body bag and while many still suffer domestic violence because it remains widespread and is often considered "socially acceptable‚Äù in nigeria. .
.
this is the reason family, friends and even some religious bodies do not see domestic violence as such a big deal. they believe it‚Äôs the outcome of provocation and admonish victims never to annoy their abusers . but these abusers don‚Äôt hit their bosses or colleagues who provoke them at work . they exercise restraints! .

domestic violence is not a result of provocation. i‚Äôm writing this in capital letters and i hope it sinks in! violence and abuse is a tool used to enforce control, power and fear in a relationship or marriage and not a momentary expression of anger.
.
so stop judging victims by saying they were battered because of an imagined, perceived or rumored wrong or asking them annoying questions like ‚Äúwhat did you do that made him beat you‚Äù. questions like these are unintelligent and insensitive.
.
violence against women isn't cultural, its criminal. real men don't use violence! we must all join hands to eliminate violence against women and girls. our women must feel and know that they are not alone! .

there is no excuse for violence against women.  and yes, no excuse for violence against men either. 
don't justify it....don't judge them!
.
i am a victim turned victor ready to help other victims. join in , let's make a difference! .
.

„Éª„Éª„Éª
hey yoga teachers: if you teach vinyasa, or lead teacher trainings, or ever ever ever teach the history of yoga, then you need to go listen to @jbrownyoga‚Äôs new interview with karen rain, who was an early devotee of pattabhi jois, and whose refusal to be silent about the sexual assault she suffered under his tutelage is changing the face of ashtanga. that‚Äôs her there in the headstand at left, in this 1993 @yogaworks primary series video. next to her are richard freeman and tim miller, who went on to become ashtanga icons. why didn‚Äôt she? because she was so traumatized by sexual assault at the hands of her ‚Äúguru‚Äù that she left her beloved practice completely, a troubling abusive pattern many fellow mysore practitioners witnessed and never called out.
.
the bottom line is that the vinyasa practice we know and love is largely a product of a serial sexual predator. gah. seriously. ü§¶üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è so if you teach yoga history (especially to starry-eyed newbie teachers!) and leave this shit out, you are lying to your students. and doing a disservice to everyone who will ever study with them.
.
the shadow side of yoga is real. it‚Äôs not pretty and it‚Äôs not fun to talk about. but karen does a powerful job here of sharing her story, calling out privilege, and saying it like it is, even when it‚Äôs uncomfortable. her voice shakes. listening, i feel her vulnerability and her bravery. and i recommit to telling the truth about the often-misogynistic history of yoga, even when it feels icky and uncomfortable.
.
we owe it to our students. be brave. do the hard work. they deserve the truth. it‚Äôs more than just rainbows and unicorns. ü¶Ñüåà
.

text:
setiap 1 dari 3 wanita indonesia pernah mengalami kekerasan setidaknya sekali dalam seumur hidupnya, tanpa memandang tingkat pendidikan, status sosial atau usia mereka. korban sering terdiam karena mereka disalahkan dan kesaksian mereka diragukan.

untuk memperingati 16 hari aktivisme tahun ini melawan kekerasan berbasis gender, para influencer indonesia menyampaikan pesan yang kuat untuk mengakhiri kekerasan terhadap perempuan dan anak perempuan. dalam video tersebut, para influencer menekankan pentingnya bagi setiap orang untuk berbicara, berdiri dalam solidaritas dengan para penyintas dan pendukung dan bertindak untuk menghentikan normalisasi kekerasan terhadap perempuan dan anak perempuan.

kekerasan terhadap perempuan bukan hanya masalah perempuan, tetapi juga masalah setiap orang. sekarang saatnya untuk berbicara agar suara kita didengar.
‚óè‚óè‚óè
every 1 out of 3 indonesian women has experienced violence at least once in her lifetime, regardless of their level of education, social status or age. victims are often driven into silence because they are blamed and their testimonies are put in doubt.

to commemorate this year's 16 days of activism against gender based violence, indonesian influencers delivering a strong message to end violence against women and girls. in the video, the influencers emphasize the importance for everyone to speak out, stand in solidarity with survivors and advocates and act in order to stop normalizing violence against women and girls.

violence against women is not just a women‚Äôs issue, but also everyone‚Äôs issue. it is now time to speak up and for our voice to be heard.

#hearmetoo #16days #orangetheworld  #metoo #unwomen #genderequality .
‚Äî un women asia and the pacific

yes i was molested .. i am ahada abdullah my not small but biggest secret of my life which took me in depression.. i was just 6 years when me and my mom went for shopping we entered in a jeans shop my mom chooses jeans for me when other person called her was talking with her and other man in a shop was checking my size then as my mom went away that man inappropriately touched me ... i was so numb to react on that time i lost my courage to speak up or tell my mom shout up for her ... mom was about to come i just left and stand by her side without uttering a word i was in blank condition ....... this was happened and it was happened till today i was scared to speak up and it was not my fault i was innocent i was a small girl just 6yrs.old ... then it happens again .. from that day too now i stopped getting out off house i hate shopping i hate enjoying out hate going out i was in condition which no one can imagine i cry all night's .. i scared to be talked with anyone .. i was sick off my self was disturb all the time was imagine things ..etc.etc 
raise your voice let people know what you feel you are a human too 
what if you was a small girl/boy ... at end u have a same shame respect like everyone ... ............................. to be honest i am still scared i am still broken still that same girl which was 6.yrs old it is very important to keep an eye on ur child's every action i will make shore my child to never suffer as i did .....will you ?

yes i was molested .. i am ahada abdullah my not small but biggest secret of my life which took me in depression.. i was just 6 years when me and my mom went for shopping we entered in a jeans shop my mom chooses jeans for me when other person called her was talking with her and other man in a shop was checking my size then as my mom went away that man inappropriately touched me ... i was so numb to react on that time i lost my courage to speak up or tell my mom shout up for her ... mom was about to come i just left and stand by her side without uttering a word i was in blank condition ....... this was happened and it was happened till today i was scared to speak up and it was not my fault i was innocent i was a small girl just 6yrs.old ... then it happens again .. from that day too now i stopped getting out off house i hate shopping i hate enjoying out hate going out i was in condition which no one can imagine i cry all night's .. i scared to be talked with anyone .. i was sick off my self was disturb all the time was imagine things ..etc.etc 
raise your voice let people know what you feel you are a human too 
what if you was a small girl/boy ... at end u have a same shame respect like everyone ... ............................. to be honest i am still scared i am still broken still that same girl which was 6.yrs old it is very important to keep an eye on ur child's every action i will make shore my child to never suffer as i did .....will you ?

#metoo #molested #behuman #raiseyourvoice
#writerahada #girl #metoo

and until december 2, 2019, a whole new set of lessons abound.‚†Ä

text:
so one of my favourite films has a real rape scene. marlon brando, playing a middle-aged recently-widowed american in paris, has a doomed affair with a teenage french student - #mariaschneider was 19 in real life too. 
on the morning of the shoot, #brando and #bertolucci decided the former's character would rape the girl in an empty flat with the help of a stick of butter, shoved in her anus. the actress (who did not have an agent or a parent at the scene) was not told about the scene, to get a 'natural, spontaneous' reaction from her. 
what happened scarred the girl for life - she suffered from major depression, took to drugs and attempted suicide many times. 
i hope you can rip, bertolucci. and brando. two famous, powerful men dehumanising a girl for a 'natural, spontaneous' scene.
#lasttangoinparis #metoo

text:
1. you seem like you are doing fine. 
it's so easy how that rolls right off your tongue so clean and simple. it makes me want to punch you in the face and send you flying across the room. you have no idea how i am doing and fine is one of the last items on my list. i may say i am doing fine but i'm not. for your own health and safety, you should just start assuming that i am a major basket case all the time and at any given moment i could start screaming and twitching uncontrollably. i may also start pulling my hair out or drawing on the walls. you just never know so don't say i'm fine. i'm not!
#sexualabusesurvivor #letstalk #thingsyoushouldneversay #survivor #awomanscorned #metoo #silentnomore

goals. 
in this house we set them. 
big. 
small. 
weekly. 
lifetime goals. 
we focus on our own but we pay attention to each other‚Äôs.
we chase our own and we cheer each other on during the others chase.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
i wanted to run 5 times this week. 
he wanted to increase his overall motivation. 
so we built momentum team work style- showed up and killed day 1 of the week which means we killed day 1 of our goals.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
yes, i am a motivational wellness coach for a living. i do use the same tools in my home and in my own life as i provide in my virtual growth groups. because this shiz works! 
message me for more details and join the party in december. finish 2018 like a badass preparing to chase more goals in the new year. ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
aim for zero is @awaresingapore latest campaign to end sexual violence in singapore. it was launched yesterday, in conjunction with international day for the elimination of violence against women. the campaign is aware‚Äôs response to the outcries against sexual violence amplified by the global #metoo movement.

said corinna lim, executive director of aware, ‚Äúwhether you are a leader, a parent, an employer, or a student, you can take concrete steps to address sexual violence. we should press for collective action by keeping one another accountable, stepping up to diligently ensure the spaces we occupy are free from harassment and violence, and be supportive first-responders to those who have been assaulted or harassed.‚Äù
.
"besides a handful of local cases on workplace and institutional harassment that received public attention, singapore has been relatively less visible in the #metoo conversation. but that doesn‚Äôt mean we weren‚Äôt touched by it. our sexual assault care centre (sacc) saw a 79% surge in cases at the end of 2017, when the #metoo movement took off. this proves that more support is needed, and concrete change needs to happen on every level ‚Äì that‚Äôs what aim for zero plans to do,‚Äù said ms. lim, who is also one of the participants of the campaign video and spoke about her experience of workplace harassment.

members of the public can show their support by pledging online, sharing the campaign video on social media with the hashtag #aimforzerosg or donating to the aim for zero fund. visit the website to learn more: aimforzero.sg

text:
"sometimes in our greatest pain, we find our greatest power." @jayshetty. when my life was "falling apart" and i left my abusive ex, and pretty much lost everything, i felt like all my doors and dreams were closing. what now? i have to restart my life over! i felt weak, scared, overwelmed and small.

fast forward almost 4 years and thank god those doors closed. because the doors that have opened for me along this healing journey have been remarkable. i've travelled, lived overseas, reignited my dream and vision, met the love of my life, reinvented myself and strengthened my relationship with god.

what i thought was my life coming unglued, was really a redirection. it didn't feel nice most of the time, but now my feelings are catching up with my heart and head.

have greater faith in yourself, in god and in the process of healing you.

still a queen üëë‚úä.
.
.
.

text:
what is rape? what can you do if you or someone you know has been raped? 
girlshealth.gov provides answers to the questions above on their website. they define rape as sex you do not agree to, including forcing a body part or object into your vagina, rectum, or mouth. while different states define rape differently in their laws (california defines rape as the penetration of a penis into the rectum or vagina), girlshealth.gov‚Äôs definition is the common consensus of what rape is.
this website also provides suggestions on what to do if you think that either you or someone you know has been raped. some of the suggestions include: don‚Äôt blame yourself, go to the police or hospital right away, get medical care right away, get emotional support, etc. girlshealth.gov also gives a few hotlines and phone numbers that you can call for help and support.
this website is overall a good source for people who want to be educated about rape or for people who are seeking help. it answers the simple questions that a lot of college students do not know. make sure to check out the website to learn more!

text:
i made this account to reconnect with friends after a period of absence from all social media, and to post my beliefs on activism and injustices i am very passionate about. 
i was preparing one of these posts, specifically one regarding the prejudice many have faced within the lgbtq+ community when suddenly, i deleted it and quickly exited the app. i told myself it was because it wasn't interesting, and it wasn't going to do anything anyway. this was a lie.
the truth was, what caused this abrupt action was a rather innocent notification i just received. a new follower, one i knew from school. 
this particular person had reacted negatively to a post of a similar fashion i made on my last account on instagram. in fact, negative is a bit of an understatement. he had been one of the many showering me in death threats, insults, and inconsiderate slurs of which i had heard way too much of. i didn't even think about it. it certainly wasn't on my mind as i was making my way down the catwalk near my highschool. 
it was peaceful, and i was alone, but this was before that caused panic that sets my every nerve on edge. 
suddenly it was like the woods around me came alive; like a strong wind had swept through the underbrush. i had no time to register just how wrong that assumption was before three teenage boys were holding me from all sides. and most of what i can remember from then on was the fear. and the pain. so, so much pain. 
for the first of it, i was sharply aware of the hand dug in my hair keeping my head up just enough to see the onslaught of punches and kicks landing everywhere from my neck to my ankles, but never my face. i heard through sharp pain the cruel muffled words describing the horrors they wished they could do to set me straight. what they would do, if i talked. why they were keeping my pretty little face intact. 
the next thing i knew i was on the cold asphalt, and the last of the brutal stomps and kicks to my ribs sent deafening cracks into the air around me, until it faded into a silence that had since kept me captive. 
not anymore.

#socialactivism #activist #lgbt #lgbtrights  #feminism #metoo #lovewins #equality

pre_proc_tweet:
i made this account to reconnect with friends after a period of absence from all social media, and to post my beliefs on activism and injustices i am very passionate about. 
i was preparing one of these posts, specifically one regarding the prejudice many have faced within the lgbtq+ community when suddenly, i deleted it and quickly exited the app. i told myself it was because it wasn't interesting, and it wasn't going to do anything anyway. this was a lie.
the truth was, what caused this abrupt action was a rather innocent notification i just received. a new follower, one i knew from school. 
this paicular person had reacted negatively to a post of a similar fashion i made on my last account on instagram. in fact, negative is a bit of an understatement. he had been one of the many showering me in death threats, insults, and inconsiderate slurs of which i had heard way too much of. i didn't even think about it. it ceainly wasn't on my mind as i was making my way down the catwalk near my highschool. 
it was peaceful, and i was alone, but this was before that caused panic that sets my every nerve on edge. 
suddenly it was like the woods around me came alive; like a strong wind had swept through the underbrush. i had no time to register just how wrong that assumption was before three teenage boys were holding me from all sides. and most of what i can remember from then on was the fear. and the pain. so, so much pain. 
for the first of it, i was sharply aware of the hand dug in my hair keeping my head up just enough to see the onslaught of punches and kicks landing everywhere from my neck to my ankles, but never my face. i heard through sharp pain the cruel muffled words describing the horrors they wished they could do to set me straight. what they would do, if i talked. why they were keeping my pretty little face intact. 
the next thing i knew i was on the cold asphalt, and the last of the brutal stomps and kicks to my ribs sent deafening cracks into the air around me, until it faded into a silence that had since kept me captive. 
not anymore.

text:
#16daysofactivism
__  @regran_ed from @mercyiaspire -  the picture on the left is me 12 years ago! then a victim now a victor! .
.
i am one of the few fortunate to be alive. some  left in a body bag and while many still suffer domestic violence because it remains widespread and is often considered "socially acceptable‚Äù in nigeria. .
.
this is the reason family, friends and even some religious bodies do not see domestic violence as such a big deal. they believe it‚Äôs the outcome of provocation and admonish victims never to annoy their abusers . but these abusers don‚Äôt hit their bosses or colleagues who provoke them at work . they exercise restraints! .

domestic violence is not a result of provocation. i‚Äôm writing this in capital letters and i hope it sinks in! violence and abuse is a tool used to enforce control, power and fear in a relationship or marriage and not a momentary expression of anger.
.
so stop judging victims by saying they were battered because of an imagined, perceived or rumored wrong or asking them annoying questions like ‚Äúwhat did you do that made him beat you‚Äù. questions like these are unintelligent and insensitive.
.
violence against women isn't cultural, its criminal. real men don't use violence! we must all join hands to eliminate violence against women and girls. our women must feel and know that they are not alone! .

there is no excuse for violence against women.  and yes, no excuse for violence against men either. 
don't justify it....don't judge them!
.
i am a victim turned victor ready to help other victims. join in , let's make a difference! .
.

text:
hear the voices of women. 
november 25 is the start of the #respetonaman campaign to end gender-based violence.

as inspired by the global #metoo, and#timesup movement and thailand's #donttellmehowtodress movement, it will focus on bringing the issue into the mainstream and empowering women to rise up against all forms of gender-based violence  particularly on rape and sexual harassment.

join us for the #respetonaman forum at francisco santiago hall, bdo south tower, makati on november 28, 2018 from 5:30 to 8:00pm and on november 29 #respetonaman university forum leong hall, ateneo de manila university 8:00 am to 12:00 pm.

learn more about #respetonaman by following the hashtag and visit the #donttellmehowtodress exhibit in power plant mall until december 1.

be on the side of women empowerment! stop the disrespect, respeto naman.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
trigger warning -
not all of these women are survivors of sexual violence, but statistically 1 in 4 women will experience rape or sexual assault in her lifetime.
-
this trailer features just some of the women‚Äôs stories you will find in our book ‚Äò100 women i know‚Äô, it‚Äôs not an easy read but a necessary one.
-
our documentary film of the same title is screening at our event this thursday. the documentary is based on 100 responses to a questionnaire about rape and sexual assault. four young women sit in their bedrooms, unapologetically telling their stories of rape. the intimate insight into these brave women‚Äôs experiences is powerful, and thought provoking. from hearing these women‚Äôs stories, and their reflections on their experiences, ‚Äò100 women i know‚Äô encourages you to consider the (often unshared) stories of the women you know.
-
this project aims to bring together and foster solidarity between everyone who has experienced sexual violence.
-
the film has been touring the film festival circuit internationally for the last 2 years. we want to continue to screen it - please get in touch if you can offer us a platform to do so. for anyone interested you can find upcoming listings on our website.
-
thank you to every person who has volunteered to work on this project wether affected or not, when we stand together in solidarity powerful things happen.
-
big love, phoebe.
-

text:
i am in shock @graziauk allowed this to be printed. are we going back to the dark ages? when i saw this it made me cry. this is the opposite to the #metoo campaign with unhealthy, backward messages. words have power grazia. please use them wisely.
yesterday a client came to breathe with me to help him deal with the grief of losing his beautiful boy at the age of 18.  his son took his own life. if he could turn the clock around he would tell his boy to please share with him when he was feeling sad and to cry in his arms whenever he needed. 
many of my clients are teenage boys and men who have anxiety and depression and don‚Äôt have tools to deal with this. i am so grateful they have the courage to be brave enough to ask for help. this is a global issue and feminist eve ensler was so right when she said. ‚Äòthose bullets are hardened tears‚Äô 
suicide is the leading cause of death for men under 45 in the uk. one reason that men are more likely to complete suicide is because they are less likely than women to ask for help or talk about depressive or suicidal feelings. 
many men come to my breathing workshops and guess what? they cry. all i see is great strength in these men and hope that we can change this patterns and old ingrained voices telling young boys to ‚Äòman up!‚Äô or ‚Äòboys don‚Äôt cry‚Äô
i encourage my little boy to share his feelings and to not be ashamed to cry or speak to me if he feels vulnerable. he also knows that crying does not mean you are weak. men in particular need to be given permission to feel. so much pain is because of unprocessed grief.
grazia i really hope you rectify this and run a piece on supporting men to speak about their feelings and that women don‚Äôt see that as unattractive. let men know it‚Äôs safe to be able to express how they feel without being persecuted or judged. we all make mistakes grazia. please take a deep breath and turn this around. thank you @mattzhaig for sharing #andbreathe #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth #alllivesmatter #bekind #breathwork #wordshavepower #bethechange

text:
self portrait. #kodak #35mm #infrared #film, shot on a #nikon, circa 2003, printed by me in a darkroom that i miss dearly, on #ilford fiber paper. 
that hair tho. #throwback to this time frame when i was dating a #crazyex, dealing with my parents‚Äô relationship fallouts and trying to find solace in someone that i thought was so cool... instead of focusing more on me. but after a series of unfortunate events over almost 2 years, ohhh the stories, that are quite crazy and very much not something i did... no cheating, no psycho shit, just eventual use of self defense on multiple occasions, all which triggered depression and anxiety about myself that still lingers, and had me not believing in myself for some dumb reason through my adulthood, oh and all the terrible things you think will ‚Äúnever happen to you‚Äù... guess what... it did, but i see through it all, and now, i don‚Äôt believe you and the lies you told me and i told myself. 
i was and still am smart, pretty, funny, happy, personable, outgoing, fun, spontaneous, creative and talented. rejection, judgement and constantly being told you‚Äôre not good enough make for a bad combo long term. you begin to not realize that you beat yourself up and say negative things about yourself, thinking it‚Äôs healthy or normal. sometimes it‚Äôs really hard knowing who to trust, or trusting yourself to really know who you are and to know how to say no. luckily, i‚Äôm still here and still sassy, so fuck all that. i still fucking kick ass. always did, always will, so #suckit #ego #get #onpoint #goinbacktocali #female #director #photographer #storyteller #truth #metoo #fuckthenaysayers #cuztheydontmeanathing #thisiswhatstylewebring

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

november 25th to december 10th. 
follow us on all platforms. link in bio. you can't afford to miss this.

text:
as someone who has struggled with depression for as long as i can remember, sleep was always my go to. something went wrong, sleep. something didn't go wrong, sleep. big test coming up, sleep. add in anxiety and p tsd, and i'm just a fun filled lollipop triple dipped in crazy. .
sleep was an out for me. my own self- medication..i can remember times i slept for 28 hours. do you think i woke up rested? no. more sleep is not always the answer.  that is especially true in the case of depression and anxiety.
.
 without getting too technical, our bodies and our brains have chemicals in them. without regular physical activity, those chemicals build-up and cause adverse reactions. i.e. anxiety. depression.
.
 exercise is the most effective anti-depressant. it is also the most under utilized anti-depressant. read that again.
.
last time you were at the doctor, did he ask you if you've been exercising? i bet she dead. why don't you give it a try? i have all the tools that you need. i can teach you. send me apm, or fill out the app in my bio. let's have a little chat, no pressure.

text:
international day for the elimination of violence against women. ( 25th november to 10th december ). we have all heard the statics, you know the one, that one in three women experience violence in their lifetime, across all social status, class, race, country or age group. and in our opinion that is one too many! this year‚Äôs un theme for the day is #hearmetoo and they are amplifying womens voices, calling for action and as always raising awareness, because as we know, knowledge is power babes. so we thought we would kick off these 16 days of activism by sharing the things which everyone should know. #orangetheworld #heartmetoo #16days #violenceagainstwomen #overthrowthepatriarchy #eliminateviolence #womensrights.  #genderbasedviolence from today, the international day to eliminate #violenceagainstwomen through 10 dec., #humanrightsday. #hearmetoo #orangetheworld #standup4humanrights 
we spotlight some of the most powerful voices driving today‚Äôs women‚Äôs rights movements including: #metoo, #niunamenos, #noustoutes. we support countless other movements today for gender equality.
