- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subve elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
a dream come true. i met her excellency, vp leni robredo.

it was during the launching of #respetonaman, the local equivalent of the #metoo movement that aims to end rape culture and violence against women, children, and all genders. she was a gracious host, and was kind enough to actually acknowledge my presence during the event. she mentioned my name in that very podium. stunning! we had a little chat, and i was fortunate enough to tell her about my advocacy for the lgbtq community.

yes. last night, i had the ultimate pleasure of having a little girl's fantasy fulfilled. to meet a woman in power and to share some thoughts with her has always been a dream.

my mom always taught me to dream big and aim high. the drag queen who was once a little boy from a little town is now breaking barriers.

this is destiny, fulfilled. this is a new beginning.

xoxo
dee dee marie

#dragqueen
#lenirobredo

@aikarobredo your mum is amazing!

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

last year, sen. kirsten gillibrand led the call for sen. al franken‚Äôs resignation after he was accused of groping or trying to forcibly kiss more than half a dozen women. now that could be hurting her shot at a 2020 presidential run.
üî∏
more than a dozen major democratic donors ‚Äì many of them women ‚Äì think gillibrand pulled the rug out from under franken, forcing him out without proper vetting of the allegations against him. the donors declared they would never again donate to or fundraise for gillibrand or would only do so if she ended up as the democratic presidential nominee.
üî∏
on the surface, their anger seems counterintuitive. during the height of the #metoo movement, gillibrand stood up to a respected colleague in her own party. it raised her national profile and branded her as a fierce female leader who wouldn't tolerate sexual harassment. but to major fundraisers, it seemed like a political move. ‚Äúi thought she was duplicitous,‚Äù one donor said. ‚Äúonce the whole thing happened with al franken, it was confirmed 1 billion percent that she‚Äôs not to be trusted.‚Äù link in bio for the full story.

text:
in today's very special and insightful episode, i interview my finnish kindred spirit, juho laaksonen. juho and i met over facebook after he wrote a review for this podcast and recommended i speak to a best selling science author from finland. we instantly had chemistry and after talking about a plethora of fascinating topics i realized he would be a perfect guest for the round table.

and he did not disappoint.

topics discussed include: education reform, climate change, feminism, how to effortlessly guide more girls into stem fields, cultivating your child‚Äôs curiosity, teaching science, the true sources of happiness, who needs the most help, teaching electricity to his daughters, neil degrasse tyson‚Äôs video on teaching science to kids being a parenting guide, emphasizing openness, a shout-out to juho‚Äôs wife‚Äôs sacrifice, life before and after having children, when he discovered his passion for science, learning from failure, his child‚Äôs desire for a laboratory, parenting vs genetics, exploring the differences between boys and girls, einstein‚Äôs quote on genius, the boredom problem, philosophy being the love of knowledge, hans rosling, misunderstanding data, the inspiring progress of humankind, our mutual admiration of sam harris, how to change fear into action, mike buckler‚Äôs story, disappointing progress in malawi from foreign aid, communicating with the extreme poor and asking what they need, what is effective altruism, why empowering women is the cure for poverty, the inspiring progress for women in bangladesh, who is highly neglected from aid, the power of micro-loans for empowerment, the disappointing lack of nuance in the #metoo movement, juho being scared as a feminist, the ramifications of #metoo in finland, the three levels of need, the appeal of round table chats, jumping on opportunities, being open to the world, online chess friendships, shrinking the world, the value of taking risks, and ‚Äúalways be yourself, unless you can be batman... then be batman." https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bikmiwrulum

text:
sunday 25 was the un international day of nonviolence against women, and it was held a demonstration in support of a consent-based law on rape.

in denmark it must be proved that the victim has been subjected to coercion, threats of violence or physical violence or was in a helpless state before a rape can be punished. in this claim, we require denmark to have rape legislation that protects victims far better than today and lives up to the council of europe convention on violence against women. danish legislation must therefore be based on consent, that is, the basic principle that sex must be voluntary. so if it is not voluntary, it is a rape. 
about 50 people oppressed the biting cold and went from vestre landsret on gabel's square down to toldbod plads. here there was talk of christine vassaux noe and aur√≠a paz, who share her talent for singing and her song ‚Äúinnerchild‚Äù related with overcome childhood sexual abuse.

if the law is passed, it definitely encourages victims to come forward and that's the beginning for a culture where women/trans/lgbt+ in general get supported instead of blamed or discredited. people at first need to understand why this is necessary and the culture of fear in which women and other vulnerable groups entail in the world. also, for men who do experience rape, it is important that their voices also get heard and that we create a culture in which this can be possible without stigmatization. the police needs to be trained more properly for such cases because there is a huge bias and they are not able to respond in a way that is safe for the victims. the taboo rape is one of them. 
a new law would allow more communication around such important issues. we (as a society) need to educate teenagers or kids in general about this, so schools should implement awareness talks about this. it needs to be normalized, because it happens.
.
.
.
.

text:
‚Äúthe violence inherited from apartheid still resonates profoundly in today‚Äôs south african society dominated by deeply entrenched patriarchal attitudes towards the role of women in society which makes violence against women and children an almost accepted social phenomenon‚Äù - the un special rapporteur on violence against women 
sexual and physical violence plagues women across a multitude of communities in south africa.
a 2012 study revealed that across four provinces 77% of women have experienced gender-based violence. 
sexual offences alone seen a 56% increase over the 2016/2017 period. 
violence against women in south africa is a problem because of its prevalence, persistence and normalisation. 
acknowledging this is the first step to creating safer spaces for women. ‚Ä¢

text:
daily affirmation and a reminder: when life brings you down just a bit too often, having hope for things to get better is scary: to get hopes high  only for them to be crushed again. 
i wish you strength to separate your hopes from fears. hope will give you fuel to breath, hope can soothe the pain. hope is a blanket for your torn soul. and then there will be another day, and eventually it will start getting better.
.

text:
when i'm lyin' in my bed at night
i don't want to grow up
nothing ever seems to turn out right
i don't want to grow up
how do you move in a world of fog that's
always changing things
makes wish that i could be a dog
when i see the price that you pay
i don't want to grow up
i don't ever want to be that way
i don't want to grow up
seems that folks turn into things
that they never want
the only thing to live for is today...
i'm gonna put a hole in my t.v. set
i don't want to grow up
open up the medicine chest
i don't want to grow up
i don't want to have to shout it out
i don't want my hair to fall out
i don't want to be filled with doubt
i don't want to be a good boy scout
i don't want to have to learn to count
i don't want to have the biggest amount
i don't want to grow up
well when i see my parents fight
i don't want to grow up
they all go out and drinkin' all night
i don't want to grow up
i'd rather stay here in my room
nothin' out there but sad and gloom
i don't want to live in a big old tomb on
grand street
when i see the 5 o'clock news
i don't want to grow up
comb their hair and shine their shoes
i don't want to grow up
stay around in my old hometown
i don't want to put no money down
i don't want to get a big old loan
work them fingers to the bone
i don't want to float on a broom
fall in love, get married then boom
how the hell did it get here so soon
i don't want to grow up

the ramones

text:
when i'm lyin' in my bed at night
i don't want to grow up
nothing ever seems to turn out right
i don't want to grow up
how do you move in a world of fog that's
always changing things
makes wish that i could be a dog
when i see the price that you pay
i don't want to grow up
i don't ever want to be that way
i don't want to grow up
seems that folks turn into things
that they never want
the only thing to live for is today...
i'm gonna put a hole in my t.v. set
i don't want to grow up
open up the medicine chest
i don't want to grow up
i don't want to have to shout it out
i don't want my hair to fall out
i don't want to be filled with doubt
i don't want to be a good boy scout
i don't want to have to learn to count
i don't want to have the biggest amount
i don't want to grow up
well when i see my parents fight
i don't want to grow up
they all go out and drinkin' all night
i don't want to grow up
i'd rather stay here in my room
nothin' out there but sad and gloom
i don't want to live in a big old tomb on
grand street
when i see the 5 o'clock news
i don't want to grow up
comb their hair and shine their shoes
i don't want to grow up
stay around in my old hometown
i don't want to put no money down
i don't want to get a big old loan
work them fingers to the bone
i don't want to float on a broom
fall in love, get married then boom
how the hell did it get here so soon
i don't want to grow up

the ramones

text:
the international day for the elimination of violence against women has passed but the data that emerged remained impressed.
global estimates published by who indicate that about 1 in 3 (35%) of women worldwide have experienced either physical and/or sexual intimate partner violence or non-partner sexual violence in their lifetime.
globally, as many as 38% of murders of women are committed by a male intimate partner.
realizing how widespread the problem is is the first step to solving it.

‚Ä¢ get a medical examination at a sane site
‚Ä¢ forensic evidence collection kit can be done
‚Ä¢ start pregnancy prophylaxis if appropriate
‚Ä¢ get sti prophylactic treatment ‚Ä¢ call your local rape crisis center to get medical advocate accompaniment

text:
at india art fiesta @coomaraswamy hall , prince of wales museum , mumbai , to support @sarayukamat my gorgeous friend (and my gypsy clairvoyant) and banker-turned-artist .... it‚Äôs a privilege and honour to witness her artwork (her inspiration behind these paintings in a separate post) ... and of course the drama queen in me cannot resist an equally dramatic pose in front of them ! .
after the art show i went all the way to bandra , mehmood studios where #wethewomen was being happening . and it was really a very happening event . panel discussions with an impressive line up of people like farhan akhtar , karan johar, waheeda rehman and the newer lot such as richa chaddha , tapsee pannu . #metoo was extensively discussed . quite a few in the audience were of the view that apart from raising our daughters to be independent and take their own decisions , sons should also be raised to respect women. 
what do you think ? love to hear ! .
saree de jour : a peach coloured kosa silk with a flaming (akin to my personality!) orange pallu contrasted with black (like my humour and my mood sometimes!) . this kosa silk saree worn in honour of saree doyenne and a very esteemed #indudiva patron vijayalaxmi chhabra @vijayalaxmichhabra who initiated #themajestyofkosa on instagram . 
thanks to her , a lot of us saree enthusiasts learnt that kosa is a variety of tussar . and that all kosa is tussar  but not all tussar is kosa . sounds like those multiple choice answers in the iim-a entrance exams . that i have seen some 20 years back ! 
ah well , we live and learn every day .
thank you di for initiating this campaign !
.
.
.

#repost @mercyiaspire (@get_repost)
„Éª„Éª„Éª
the picture on the left is me 12 years ago! then a victim now a victor! .
.
i am one of the few fortunate to be alive. some  left in a body bag and while many still suffer domestic violence because it remains widespread and is often considered "socially acceptable‚Äù in nigeria. .
.
this is the reason family, friends and even some religious bodies do not see domestic violence as such a big deal. they believe it‚Äôs the outcome of provocation and admonish victims never to annoy their abusers . but these abusers don‚Äôt hit their bosses or colleagues who provoke them at work . they exercise restraints! .

domestic violence is not a result of provocation. i‚Äôm writing this in capital letters and i hope it sinks in! violence and abuse is a tool used to enforce control, power and fear in a relationship or marriage and not a momentary expression of anger.
.
so stop judging victims by saying they were battered because of an imagined, perceived or rumored wrong or asking them annoying questions like ‚Äúwhat did you do that made him beat you‚Äù. questions like these are unintelligent and insensitive.
.
violence against women isn't cultural, its criminal. real men don't use violence! we must all join hands to eliminate violence against women and girls. our women must feel and know that they are not alone! .

there is no excuse for violence against women.  and yes, no excuse for violence against men either. don't justify it....don't judge them.

i am a victim turned victor ready to help other victims. join in, let's make a difference! .

turns into a social entrepreneur for women influencers

the ‚Äòyaariyan‚Äô actress evelyn sharma speaks about her views on the  movement that has currently hit bollywood‚Äôs shores, she speaks about how she is currently focusing on giving women in the enteainment industry a safe backing by turning into a social entrepreneur with her new venture, her very own image development company which caters to women influencers.

sharma, who staed her career as an international model in 2008 and debuted in her first bollywood film in 2012, says: ‚Äúi‚Äôve been in this industry for a long time and have experienced a lot of disrespectful behavior towards women. i left the talent agency that managed me in the sta of my film career because of that reason and since then hired and trained my own team. it‚Äôs a common thing to say that a girl (or boy) needs a godfather to make it in the industry, but i would like to differ. i think it needs talent, good management, and a big poion of courage to stick to your own beliefs. i never had a godfather, however i make a great living off the kind of projects i choose and get to work with amazing people. there will always be trolls trying to stand in your way, but that‚Äôs no reason to give up! the whole world will tell you what path to take, how to look, and whom to fraternize with - but who are you and what are your dreams? i‚Äôve discovered being true to yourself is where real happiness awaits you and had the honor to encourage others by sharing my story of overcoming struggles with identity at various events, like the us president‚Äôs national prayer breakfast in washington d.c.‚Äù witnessing all the change this movement is bringing, she came across an idea of how she could better the situation by helping women influencers and celebrities, that‚Äôs when her idea was born. she decided to build a strong team of professionals for herself and for her friends in the industry to help them grow and release her full potential. she believes that we are all in the process of growing and realizing our own potential, in her words, we are all a ‚Äúwork in progress‚Äù, and need a slight push to reach our full potential. her new venture wip creat

today is the day!!! as a nonprofit, crisis services is largely dependent on donations from folks in our community in order to sustain many of the services we provide.

for example, the demand for our hotline never wavers but our funding does.

although our services + costs increase, our funding remains stagnant‚Ä¶

every day our #crisisfirstresponders work to combat the increasing rate of suicide, create a community of belief & support responding to the #metoo movement and provide critical intervention for those addicted.

we answer the call. but with increased demand comes increased cost‚Ä¶

help us ensure every call is answered 24 hours a day.

your donation can help guarantee that from this moment forward no one is ever alone.

invest in a mission that saves lives ‚Äì click the link in our bio to donate to @crisisservices today! #givingtuesday

text:
to amanda kelly, 
global news and all montrealers. 
mom lied!! false allegations and perjury is a criminal offence.
mom did this knowing i would be detained in prison so that she could run off with my daughter.
she has done the same to the two previous fathers of her children.
i was never convicted. i got out of prison only to search for my daughter who is in danger with that woman.
my daughter was located in toronto and has inflicted harm. her half brother was sent to a children's hospital in toronto where mom was hiding under a different name. 
i have the right to defend myself and expose this madness that the laval police department intentionally neglected to investigate even after i've been begging them for help years before mom's lies.

there are no other victims, it never happened. the only victim is my daughter. 
i was a great father to this little girl. she was happy here with me. mom needed to get rid of me and leave the province with my daughter. 
this case is now in two different provinces in family courts, criminal courts and civil court procedures. 
here is the link to the fake news article that was printed on me. october 28, 2014 (posted below). i strongly suggest the journalist that printed that without doing any research of his/her own to take it down. 
mom is going to jail. 
remember my words. 
children have been hurt and families destroyed by one woman's lies and violence. it took her two minuets to make a call and do all this damage but it's taking me over four years to be heard. see the difference? 
signed...stephanos chrysanthe svourenos

text:
are you embracing the story of your life, and learning from your pain? or are you hiding from it in hopes one day it will all just fade away?
.
.
.
i remember when all i wanted to do was close my eyes and somehow wish away the pain that was inside of me from experiences of my past.  why did i allow myself to become as heavy as i had?  why couldn't i get this magical "willpower" everyone always talked about and finally stop quitting.  why did toxic relationships find me, and why did i stay?  why did i allow friendships to only be one sided with me giving every ounce of myself without any return?  why did i never believe i was enough?
.
.
.
it wasn't until i decided to come out from under the blanket of my past with some major inner work that i finally was able to understand why.  hiding from your past doesn't help you heal.  hiding from your past doesn't help you stop sabotaging every effort you make.  hiding from your past doesn't help you break the cycle.
.
.
.
did you know that every day i still have to make the choice on whether or not i will love myself best today or sneak back into old (and comfortable) patterns?  did you know that i still start my day off with affirmations, time alone, and surrounding myself with tools that protect my emotional energy?  i do.  and i share this with you because some of you have this idea in your head that you'll one day just not have to try any longer and things will be easy as pie.  that's not how this works.
.
.
.
you are the result of lifelong patterns and thoughts that were a part of you before you were even born.  trying to erase all of that is impossible. however, learning to understand it, embrace it, and break the cycle is how you heal.  that is how you grow.  stop trying to hide from your past in hopes it will not effect you anymore.  instead, choose today to begin to love the person you were when those bad patterns began.  you didn't love her then, but you can love her now.
name: Bri | Female Empowerment Coach
